Perspectives for the Sino-American relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations unsettled large parts of Asia.
Last year, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly pompous "state visit plus" in Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric would finally belong to the past afterwards.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump government has replaced the "strategic engagement" of the US in China with "strategic competition".
In addition, the US-American, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is great uncertainty on the financial markets, China's growth is slowing down, and in Europe, while in America higher interest rates are starting to take effect.
Uncertainty about the future development of the nuclear talks with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What are the prospects for the Sino-American relations in 2019?
It is likely that there will be an agreement by March on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions that China will make in this regard.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the envisaged timeframe.
If tariffs were negotiated one by one, a year could pass.
If Chinese economic reformers were to adopt a more drastic approach by gradually committing to the abolition of all tariffs and urging the Americans to follow suit, a quicker outcome might be possible.
That would, however, run counter to Chinese trade officials who have been schooled for decades to be tight-fisted, let alone give everything up at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Notwithstanding, a reform is something different from the way contractual agreements could be implemented in practice, even if there were no specific provisions for technology transfer.
Intellectual property protection is, however, extremely problematic.
Earlier agreements made under the administration of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
The enforcement or judicial proceedings in cases of violations of intellectual property rights remain, however, a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism would be to subject relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international commercial arbitration tribunals seated in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically mandated to enforce intellectual property protection.
Should China raise objections, it could develop its own international commercial arbitration procedure seated in China.
For this to happen, however, it would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel to enhance its international credibility.
No one trusts Chinese trade courts.
For its own domestic reform needs, China would have to move towards entirely independent commercial and civil courts within its judicial system, even if the criminal chamber remains under political control.
The US concerns about state subsidies within the framework of China's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be dispelled.
It is a fact that all countries provide some level of state support to their domestic technology sectors, even if it is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, compliance would be difficult to assess.
I am not optimistic that a negotiation outcome will be reached in this area.
Perhaps America must simply outspend China in research and development, particularly in the areas of information technology and biotechnology, by increasing public investments in these sectors.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China might offer tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
China might eventually decide to take the drastic step of agreeing on tariff-free trade not only with the US, but with all WTO member states.
In this way, China would have a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as an advocate for global free trade and curb the trend towards protectionism.
In the event of such a shift, China might seek the membership of the TPP member states, in an attempt to outdo the US (which had withdrawn from the trade agreement as one of Trump's first acts) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political opening and a market to enter.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have decreased since Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's recent visit to Beijing.
In light of the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the US, China is likely to focus in 2019 on general foreign and security policy on de-escalating conflicts in its relations with other countries.
In its relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a significant decrease in Chinese incursions into the area surrounding the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China aims to reduce tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea by hastening the negotiation of a "Code of Conduct".
In addition, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China may begin to soften its stance towards Taiwan, in light of the electoral setback suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, who advocates for independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would radically change if the US were to continue with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely to happen.
Incidents at sea with the US in the South China Sea will continue to occur, and the conflict may escalate if the US were to assert its stance on "freedom of navigation" more forcefully next year.
In all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project "New Silk Road".
In recent months, however, the initiative has caused less political commotion in China.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's transfer of the Hambantota port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns about the long-term financiability of the New Silk Road.
In 2019, therefore, triumphal reports on the New Silk Road might be less frequent to hear.
In addition, China is likely to consolidate and strengthen its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It is likely to continue to appear as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More measured representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it's better to focus on existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially if the US consistently shows disdain for it.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the US and ease tensions with other countries, its leadership is likely to use 2019 to form a well-informed opinion about the future of US policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that America's stance towards China has undergone a profound shift, they are still uncertain about the exact form this change will take and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is indicated.
